Thank you for raising that concern — you were absolutely right, and we've already addressed it.

The elevation policy has been scoped specifically to COM port properties only and does not grant broad Device Manager access. Here's what was implemented:

- Target process: DeviceProperties.exe (the actual process triggered when clicking 'Change Settings')
- Parameters restricted to: ACPI\PNP0501 (the universal ACPI hardware ID for native serial COM ports)
- Parent process locked to: mmc.exe (Device Manager only)
- Publisher verified as: Microsoft Windows

This means the elevation will only trigger when a user opens properties for a native COM port device. Any other device in Device Manager (network adapters, display, audio, USB, etc.) will not be elevated and will continue to prompt for admin credentials as usual.

